      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Best Medicine</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Forty-two New Jersey hospitals have fun centers for young patients; centers, developed by Nintendo of America and Starlight Foundation, bring television set, VCR and Super Nintendo Game to bed-ridden children; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>It's no fun being in the hospital.</p>
        <p>But 42 New Jersey hospitals are trying to give young patients a reason to smile. Their medicine includes Fun Centers developed by Nintendo of America in association with the Starlight Foundation of New York, the tri-state chapter of the international nonprofit group that serves critically, chronically and terminally ill children.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>It's no fun being in the hospital.</p>
        <p>But 42 New Jersey hospitals are trying to give young patients a reason to smile. Their medicine includes Fun Centers developed by Nintendo of America in association with the Starlight Foundation of New York, the tri-state chapter of the international nonprofit group that serves critically, chronically and terminally ill children.</p>
        <p>Starlight says studies show that children experience less pain when they use the Fun Center, which takes a television set, a VCR and a Super Nintendo Game System right to patients who can't get out of bed. One 16-year-old said: ''The medicine makes my head dizzy. I'd rather play Nintendo instead. It works just as good.'' The latest New Jersey hospitals to test the theory are Morristown Memorial and Overlook in Summit.</p>
        <p>More information is available from the Starlight Foundation at (212) 354-2878.</p>
        <p>BY THE WAY</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
